# Day G1 — Git Fundamentals: The Mental Model

> **Time budget:** 2–4 hours of focused work.
> **Prerequisite:** A terminal. Nothing else.
> **Outcome:** You understand the three-zone model, can create commits, and write professional commit messages.

---

## Why This Day Matters

Most developers learn Git as a list of commands to memorize: `git add`, `git commit`, `git push`. This is backwards. Git is not a list of commands — it
is a **content-addressable filesystem with a version-control interface on top**. Once you understand what Git is actually tracking, every command becomes self-evident.

You are about to build Achilles — an offensive security orchestration engine. Every line you write, every design decision you make, every bug you fix will be
preserved in Git's history. That history is not just a safety net. It is **evidence of how you think**. When a potential employer, a conference reviewer,
or an open-source contributor looks at your project, they will look at your commit history before they look at your code.

A clean, well-structured commit history says: *"This person understands software development as a discipline."* A messy history says: *"This person writes code. Sometimes it works."*

Start right. Today.

