## Part 1: The Three-Zone Mental Model

Before you touch a single command, understand these three concepts. Everything in Git flows between these three zones:

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                     THE THREE ZONES OF GIT                       │
├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│                                                                 │
│   ┌───────────────────┐                                         │
│   │  Working Directory │  ← The files you see and edit on disk  │
│   │  (your editor)     │     You change them with your editor.  │
│   └────────┬──────────┘                                         │
│            │                                                    │
│            │  git add                                           │
│            ▼                                                    │
│   ┌───────────────────┐                                         │
│   │   Staging Area     │  ← A snapshot you are composing.       │
│   │   (the index)      │     Not saved to history yet.          │
│   └────────┬──────────┘     Think of it as a "draft" of your    │
│            │                next commit.                         │
│            │  git commit                                        │
│            ▼                                                    │
│   ┌───────────────────┐                                         │
│   │   Repository       │  ← The permanent, compressed history   │
│   │   (.git directory) │     of all snapshots you've made.      │
│   └───────────────────┘     Immutable. Cryptographically hashed.│
│                                                                 │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

**The key insight:** `git add` does NOT save anything. It moves changes from your working directory to the staging area — like placing items on a table
before putting them in a box. `git commit` is what seals the box and puts it on the shelf. This two-step process exists for a reason: it lets you compose
a commit from specific changes, not just "everything I modified."

**Why this matters for Achilles:** When you're implementing the nmap transformer (Day 8), you might edit the transformer code AND fix a typo in a comment
AND refactor an import. Those are three separate logical changes. With the staging area, you commit them separately — each with its own message, each reviewable
independently. This is professional development.

