## Part 3: Commit Message Discipline

This is not optional. Learn it now. Never unlearn it.

### The Format

```
type(component): short imperative description
```

### Types

| Type | When to use | Example |
|------|------------|---------|
| `feat` | Adding new functionality | `feat(nmap): add XML parser for service detection` |
| `fix` | Fixing a bug | `fix(scope): handle wildcard domains with leading dot` |
| `test` | Adding or modifying tests | `test(adc): add snapshot tests for Host serialization` |
| `docs` | Documentation only | `docs(readme): add installation instructions` |
| `refactor` | Restructuring code without changing behavior | `refactor(engine): extract DAG builder into separate module` |
| `chore` | Build, CI, tooling | `chore(ci): add cargo clippy to GitHub Actions` |
| `perf` | Performance improvement | `perf(transformer): use zero-copy parsing for nmap XML` |

### The Litmus Test

Every commit message should complete this sentence:

> *"If applied, this commit will..."* → **your message here**

- ✅ `feat(scope): add CIDR range matching to scope enforcer` → "If applied, this commit will add CIDR range matching to scope enforcer."
- ❌ `fixed stuff` → "If applied, this commit will fixed stuff." — grammatically broken, semantically empty.
- ❌ `wip` → "If applied, this commit will wip." — meaningless.
- ❌ `changes` → "If applied, this commit will changes." — useless.

### Why This Matters for Achilles

When you're debugging a scope enforcement bug on Day 20, you will run `git log --oneline --grep="scope"` and see:

```
a3b2c1d feat(scope): add three-point enforcement (pre, per-node, post)
f4e5d6c fix(scope): handle excluded subdomain under wildcard
9a8b7c6 feat(scope): add CIDR range matching
1d2e3f4 feat(scope): add scope enforcement struct for domain and IP rules
```

Every commit about scope, in order, with a clear description. You can `git show a3b2c1d` to see exactly what changed when you added three-point enforcement. You
can `git diff 9a8b7c6..a3b2c1d` to see every change between CIDR matching and three-point enforcement.

This is not possible with `"wip"` and `"fix stuff"` messages.

