## Part 4: Key Concepts to Internalize

Before marking this day complete, verify you can answer each of these from memory:

| Question | Your Answer Should Include |
|----------|--------------------------|
| What are the three zones in Git? | Working directory, staging area (index), repository (.git) |
| What does `git add` do? | Moves changes from working directory → staging area |
| What does `git commit` do? | Moves the staging area → repository (creates a permanent snapshot) |
| What does `git status` show? | The state of all three zones — what's changed, what's staged, what's committed |
| What does `git diff` show? | Differences between working directory and staging area |
| What is `git add -p`? | Patch mode — stage specific hunks, not entire files |
| Why does the staging area exist? | To compose commits from specific changes (one logical change per commit) |
| What is a commit hash? | SHA-1 hash of the tree + parent + author + timestamp + message — unique ID, tamper-evident |
| What does `HEAD` point to? | The current branch, which points to the latest commit |
| What's wrong with `git commit -m "fix stuff"`? | No type, no component, no description. Useless in history. |

